title.narrative: ACCESS TO QUALITY, INTEGRATED FACILITY-BASED SERVICES

description.narrative: Under-five children and pregnant women have increased access to quality integrated facility-based health and nutrition services,which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Immunization (Covid), Maternal And Newborn Health, Maternal And Newborn Health (Covid), Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, children and women, especially the most vulnerable and hard-to-reach, utilise more quality essential health and nutrition services and benefit from positive health and nutrition care practices.

title.narrative: Under-five children and pregnant women have increased access to quality integrated facility-based health and nutrition services

description.narrative: In 2019, UNICEF contributed to the treatment of more than 52,343 new cases of severe malnutrition, 30,000 women at risk for sexual infection were screened and 12 health facilities were rehabilitated with capacities of health care providers improved on investigating cause of deaths. 210 health facilities were provided with Solar fridges for adequate vaccine storage, resulting in 98% coverage for the third dose of pentavalent vaccine and 75% of children completely immunized. A catch-up campaign in June immunized 82% of children 18-23 months with measles and rubella second dose and reached 94% vitamin A supplementation. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:27/12/2019
